      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">A 32-year-old woman presents to her primary care physician with concerns about her behavior. She reports that she has been experiencing irresistible urges to set fires, which she has acted upon several times in the past few months. She feels relief after setting the fires but later feels guilty and ashamed. She has not experienced any legal consequences yet but is worried about her safety and the safety of others. Based on her symptoms, what is the most likely diagnosis?</span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q8211311",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 15467,
      "difficulty_level": "beginner",
      "subjects_id": [
        16
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Ans. C) Pyromania</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Option C:</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">The behavior described by the patient, specifically the <strong>irresistible urges to set fires, acting upon these urges</strong>, and the <strong>subsequent feelings of relief followed by guilt and shame</strong>, aligns with the diagnostic criteria for <strong>pyromania</strong>. <strong>Pyromania</strong> is characterized by the <strong>deliberate and purposeful setting of fires</strong>, with <strong>tension or affective arousal</strong> before the act and gratification or relief when setting or witnessing the fire.</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong><u>Explanation</u>:</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Option A. Kleptomania&nbsp;</strong>is an <strong>impulse control disorder</strong> characterized by the <strong>recurrent and irresistible urge to steal items</strong> that are not needed for personal use or monetary value.</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Option B. Intermittent explosive disorder&nbsp;</strong>involves <strong>recurrent episodes of impulsive, aggressive behavior</strong> that is <strong>disproportionate to the precipitating stressor</strong>.</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Option D. Compulsive sexual behavior disorder&nbsp;</strong>is characterized by a <strong>persistent pattern of failure to control intense</strong>, <strong>repetitive sexual impulses</strong> or urges, resulting in <strong>repetitive sexual behavior</strong>.&nbsp;</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong><u>Educational objective:</u></strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Pyromania&nbsp;</strong>is an <strong>impulse control disorder</strong> characterized by an <strong>irresistible urge to set fires, tension before the act</strong>, and <strong>relief or pleasure afterward</strong>. It is <strong>distinct from other impulse control disorders like kleptomania</strong> (compulsive stealing) and intermittent explosive disorder (sudden aggressive outbursts), as well as from compulsive sexual behavior disorder.</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong><u>Ref</u>: Kaplan &amp; Sadockâ€™s Synopsis of Psychiatry, 12th edition, Page No 553.&nbsp;</strong></span></p>",
