      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\">A 35-year-old woman is brought to the psychiatrist by her family after she was caught shoplifting at a local store. She has a history of similar incidents. She expresses guilt and shame about her actions and reports that she experiences an increasing sense of tension before the act, and relief and gratification afterwards. The items stolen are not of personal use or monetary value to her. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?</span></span></span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q8401440",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 23776,
      "difficulty_level": "beginner",
      "subjects_id": [
        16
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\">Ans. C) Kleptomania</span></span></span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\">Option C:</span></span></span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\">Kleptomania&nbsp;</span></span></span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\">is characterized by <strong>recurrent failure to resist impulses to steal items</strong> that are <strong>not needed for personal use or for their monetary value</strong>. <strong>Individuals with kleptomania</strong> experience <strong>tension before the act and relief or gratification afterward</strong>. They often steal things of little value and may give them away or throw them away afterward. The stealing is not committed to express anger or vengeance and is not in response to a delusion or hallucination.</span></span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\">Explanation</span></span></span></u></strong><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\">:</span></span></span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\">Option A. Bipolar disorder:&nbsp;</span></span></span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\">While <strong>impulse control can be a problem in the manic phases of bipolar disorder</strong>, the <strong>recurrent nature of the stealing</strong> and the <strong>specific pattern of tension</strong> and relief described in the vignette is more characteristic of kleptomania.</span></span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\">Option B. Antisocial personality disorder:&nbsp;</span></span></span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\">People with an <strong>antisocial personality disorder may engage in stealing</strong>, but it is <strong>usually for personal gain</strong>, and they <strong>do not typically experience tension</strong> before the act or relief afterward in the same way someone with kleptomania does.</span></span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\">Option D. Generalized anxiety disorder</span></span></span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\">: This disorder is characterized by <strong>chronic, excessive worry about a variety of topics</strong>, but it does not involve the impulse control issues seen in kleptomania.</span></span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\">Educational Objective: </span></span></span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\">Kleptomania&nbsp;</span></span></span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\">is characterized by <strong>repetitive episodes of stealing</strong>, the <strong>stolen items are usually of no value to the individual</strong>. There is an <strong>impulse to steal followed by a feeling of increasing tension</strong>. After stealing, there is a sense of relief or even gratification. After some time, the individual feels guilt.</span></span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\">Ref</span></span></span></u></strong><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\">: Kaplan &amp; Sadock&rsquo;s Synopsis of Psychiatry, 12th edition, Page No 553.</span></span></span></strong></span></span></p>",
